ğŸ“º Episode 4: Input Types & Schema Design in GraphQL
Goal: Learn how to use GraphQL input types to clean up mutation arguments and build better schemas.

ğŸ™ Narration Script
*"Welcome back to the GraphQL tutorial series!

So far, weâ€™ve built queries and mutations â€” we can fetch books, add them, update them, and even delete them. Thatâ€™s awesome!

Butâ€¦ our schema is starting to get a little messy. Look at the addBook mutation: it takes title and author as separate arguments. What if later we want to add year, genre, or publisher? Weâ€™d have to keep adding more arguments, and that can get out of hand.

Thatâ€™s where input types come in.

Input types let us group related arguments into a single structured object. It makes our schema cleaner, more readable, and easier to maintain.

In this episode, weâ€™ll refactor our schema to use input types for mutations. Letâ€™s dive into the code!"*

ğŸ“š Lesson Structure
Intro â€“ Recap mutations, problem of too many arguments.

Explanation â€“ What input types are, why they help.

Demo â€“ Refactor addBook and updateBook to use input types.

Recap â€“ Cleaner schema design with inputs.

ğŸ’» Demo (Code to Copy-Paste)
Step 1: Update index.js
Replace with:

const { ApolloServer, gql } = require('apollo-server');

// Schema
const typeDefs = gql`
  type Book {
    title: String
    author: String
    year: Int
    genre: String
  }

  input BookInput {
    title: String!
    author: String!
    year: Int
    genre: String
  }

  input UpdateBookInput {
    title: String!
    newAuthor: String
    newYear: Int
    newGenre: String
  }

  type Query {
    books: [Book]
    book(title: String!): Book
  }

  type Mutation {
    addBook(input: BookInput!): Book
    updateBook(input: UpdateBookInput!): Book
    deleteBook(title: String!): String
  }
`;

// Sample data
let books = [
  { title: "The Hobbit", author: "J.R.R. Tolkien", year: 1937, genre: "Fantasy" },
  { title: "1984", author: "George Orwell", year: 1949, genre: "Dystopian" },
  { title: "Clean Code", author: "Robert C. Martin", year: 2008, genre: "Programming" }
];

// Resolvers
const resolvers = {
  Query: {
    books: () => books,
    book: (_, args) => books.find(b => b.title === args.title),
  },
  Mutation: {
    addBook: (_, { input }) => {
      books.push(input);
      return input;
    },
    updateBook: (_, { input }) => {
      const book = books.find(b => b.title === input.title);
      if (!book) throw new Error("Book not found");

      if (input.newAuthor) book.author = input.newAuthor;
      if (input.newYear) book.year = input.newYear;
      if (input.newGenre) book.genre = input.newGenre;

      return book;
    },
    deleteBook: (_, { title }) => {
      const index = books.findIndex(b => b.title === title);
      if (index === -1) throw new Error("Book not found");
      books.splice(index, 1);
      return `${title} was deleted successfully.`;
    }
  }
};

// Apollo Server
const server = new ApolloServer({ typeDefs, resolvers });

server.listen().then(({ url }) => {
  console.log(`ğŸš€ Server ready at ${url}`);
});
Step 2: Restart server
node index.js
