ğŸ“º Episode 5: Relationships in GraphQL (One-to-Many & Many-to-Many)
Goal: Learn how to connect different types in GraphQL schemas, like authors having books.

ğŸ™ Narration Script
*"Welcome back to the GraphQL tutorial series!

So far, weâ€™ve worked with a single type â€” Book. That was nice, but real-world data is rarely flat. Books have authors, authors may write multiple books, and books can belong to genres.

This is where relationships come in.

GraphQL lets us connect types together, just like how data relates in a database. In this episode, weâ€™ll create an Author type and connect it with our Book type. That way, we can query an author and automatically fetch all their books, or query a book and fetch its author.

Letâ€™s get into the code!"*

ğŸ“š Lesson Structure
Intro â€“ Recap input types, introduce relationships.

Explanation â€“ One-to-many (author â†’ books), many-to-many (book â†’ genres).

Demo â€“ Add Author type, connect books to authors.

Recap â€“ How resolvers handle nested data.

ğŸ’» Demo (Code to Copy-Paste)
Step 1: Update index.js
const { ApolloServer, gql } = require('apollo-server');

// Schema
const typeDefs = gql`
  type Book {
    title: String
    author: Author
    year: Int
    genre: String
  }

  type Author {
    name: String
    books: [Book]
  }

  input BookInput {
    title: String!
    authorName: String!
    year: Int
    genre: String
  }

  type Query {
    books: [Book]
    book(title: String!): Book
    authors: [Author]
    author(name: String!): Author
  }

  type Mutation {
    addBook(input: BookInput!): Book
  }
`;

// Sample data
let authors = [
  { name: "J.R.R. Tolkien" },
  { name: "George Orwell" },
  { name: "Robert C. Martin" }
];

let books = [
  { title: "The Hobbit", authorName: "J.R.R. Tolkien", year: 1937, genre: "Fantasy" },
  { title: "1984", authorName: "George Orwell", year: 1949, genre: "Dystopian" },
  { title: "Clean Code", authorName: "Robert C. Martin", year: 2008, genre: "Programming" }
];

// Resolvers
const resolvers = {
  Query: {
    books: () => books,
    book: (_, { title }) => books.find(b => b.title === title),
    authors: () => authors,
    author: (_, { name }) => authors.find(a => a.name === name),
  },
  Mutation: {
    addBook: (_, { input }) => {
      const { title, authorName, year, genre } = input;

      // Ensure author exists, if not add them
      let author = authors.find(a => a.name === authorName);
      if (!author) {
        author = { name: authorName };
        authors.push(author);
      }

      const newBook = { title, authorName, year, genre };
      books.push(newBook);
      return newBook;
    },
  },
  Book: {
    author: (book) => authors.find(a => a.name === book.authorName),
  },
  Author: {
    books: (author) => books.filter(b => b.authorName === author.name),
  }
};

// Apollo Server
const server = new ApolloServer({ typeDefs, resolvers });

server.listen().then(({ url }) => {
  console.log(`ğŸš€ Server ready at ${url}`);
});
Step 2: Restart server
node index.js
Step 3: Test Relationships
âœ… Get all books with their authors:

query {
  books {
    title
    author {
      name
    }
  }
}
âœ… Get an author and their books:

query {
  author(name: "George Orwell") {
    name
    books {
      title
      year
    }
  }
}
âœ… Add a book with a new author:

mutation {
  addBook(input: {
    title: "Animal Farm"
    authorName: "George Orwell"
    year: 1945
    genre: "Satire"
  }) {
    title
    author {
      name
    }
  }
}
