ğŸ“º Episode 6: Fragments & Reusing Queries in GraphQL
Goal: Learn how to avoid repetition and make queries reusable with GraphQL fragments.

ğŸ™ Narration Script
*"Welcome back to the GraphQL tutorial series!

So far, weâ€™ve learned queries, mutations, input types, and even relationships between types. Our API is becoming powerful. But you might have noticed something: our queries are getting repetitive.

For example, when we query books, we often ask for title, author, and maybe year. And when we query an authorâ€™s books, we also ask for title, author, and year. Copy-pasting those fields everywhere isnâ€™t ideal.

Thatâ€™s where fragments come in.

Fragments let us define a reusable set of fields, and then use them across multiple queries. It makes queries cleaner, avoids duplication, and keeps everything consistent.

Letâ€™s see how fragments work in action!"*

ğŸ“š Lesson Structure
Intro â€“ Recap queries/relationships, problem of repetition.

Explanation â€“ What fragments are, why they help.

Demo â€“ Create a BookDetails fragment, reuse it in queries.

Recap â€“ DRY principle in GraphQL queries.

ğŸ’» Demo (Code to Copy-Paste)
ğŸ‘‰ Good news: No changes needed to the server code from Episode 5. Weâ€™ll just write smarter queries with fragments.

Step 1: Query without fragments (repetitive)
query {
  books {
    title
    year
    genre
    author {
      name
    }
  }
  author(name: "George Orwell") {
    name
    books {
      title
      year
      genre
      author {
        name
      }
    }
  }
}
Notice how title, year, genre, author { name } is repeated.

Step 2: Use a fragment to clean this up
query {
  books {
    ...BookDetails
  }
  author(name: "George Orwell") {
    name
    books {
      ...BookDetails
    }
  }
}

fragment BookDetails on Book {
  title
  year
  genre
  author {
    name
  }
}
âœ… Same result, but much cleaner and reusable.

Step 3: Example Response
{
  "data": {
    "books": [
      { "title": "The Hobbit", "year": 1937, "genre": "Fantasy", "author": { "name": "J.R.R. Tolkien" } },
      { "title": "1984", "year": 1949, "genre": "Dystopian", "author": { "name": "George Orwell" } },
      { "title": "Clean Code", "year": 2008, "genre": "Programming", "author": { "name": "Robert C. Martin" } }
    ],
    "author": {
      "name": "George Orwell",
      "books": [
        { "title": "1984", "year": 1949, "genre": "Dystopian", "author": { "name": "George Orwell" } },
        { "title": "Animal Farm", "year": 1945, "genre": "Satire", "author": { "name": "George Orwell" } }
      ]
    }
  }
}
