Where are we usually storing data for graphql 
ChatGPT said:
Excellent question ğŸ‘Œ â€” this gets to the heart of how GraphQL works in real-world apps.

Hereâ€™s the key idea:

ğŸ‘‰ GraphQL itself doesnâ€™t store data.
Itâ€™s just a query language and runtime. The actual data usually lives somewhere else, and GraphQL resolvers are responsible for fetching it.

ğŸ“Œ Where data is usually stored for GraphQL
Databases (most common)

SQL databases â†’ PostgreSQL, MySQL, MariaDB, etc.

NoSQL databases â†’ MongoDB, DynamoDB, Cassandra, etc.
GraphQL resolvers run SQL/NoSQL queries under the hood.

Other APIs

GraphQL can sit on top of REST APIs or external services.

Example: A company has multiple microservices (user service, payment service, order service). GraphQL acts as a gateway, combining them into a single schema.

In-memory / temporary storage

For prototyping or small apps, data might just live in arrays/objects in memory (like we did in Episode 2).

Not persistent â€” data disappears when the server restarts.

Hybrid

Some fields from a database, others from a third-party API, maybe even some computed on the fly.

Example: Book data comes from PostgreSQL, but Author profile picture comes from an external API.

ğŸ“Š Diagram (good for slides)
Client Query â†’ GraphQL Server â†’ Resolver â†’ Data Source
                                         â†³ Database (SQL/NoSQL)
                                         â†³ REST API
                                         â†³ Microservice
                                         â†³ Cache (Redis)
ğŸ› ï¸ Real-World Example
Letâ€™s say weâ€™re building a Hotel Booking System (like in your Spring Cloud series).

Hotel and Room data â†’ PostgreSQL

Payments â†’ Stripe API

Notifications â†’ Internal microservice

GraphQL ties it all together, so the frontend just queries one endpoint.

âœ… So in short: GraphQL doesnâ€™t store the data â€” it fetches from wherever you decide.
In tutorials, we start with arrays in memory. In production, itâ€™s almost always databases and APIs.

