ğŸ“º Episode 6: Relationships in GraphQL with MySQL (Books & Authors)
Goal: Link Books â†’ Authors properly with foreign keys, and query them in GraphQL.

ğŸ™ Narration Script
*"Welcome back!

So far, our API can create, read, update, and delete books. But notice something â€” each book just stores the authorâ€™s name as a string. That works for demos, but in the real world, authors are separate entities.

Imagine if one author writes multiple books. With our current setup, weâ€™d just copy-paste their name again and again. Thatâ€™s messy, and it makes updates painful.

Today, weâ€™re going to normalize our database:

Books will have an authorId.

Authors will live in their own authors table.

In GraphQL, youâ€™ll be able to query a book and get the author details automatically.

Letâ€™s build it step by step."*

ğŸ“š Lesson Structure
Intro â€“ Problem with plain-text authors.

Database Setup â€“ Add authors table + foreign key in books.

GraphQL Schema â€“ Add Author type, link Book â†’ Author.

Resolvers â€“ Fetch related data from MySQL.

Demo â€“ Query nested relationships.

Recap â€“ Clean, relational GraphQL API.

ğŸ’» Step 1: Update Database
-- Create authors table
CREATE TABLE authors (
  id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
  name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL
);

-- Modify books table to use authorId instead of author string
ALTER TABLE books
  DROP COLUMN author,
  ADD COLUMN authorId INT,
  ADD CONSTRAINT fk_author FOREIGN KEY (authorId) REFERENCES authors(id);
ğŸ’» Step 2: Update GraphQL Schema
const typeDefs = gql`
  type Author {
    id: ID!
    name: String!
    books: [Book!]!
  }

  type Book {
    id: ID!
    title: String!
    author: Author!
  }

  input AddAuthorInput {
    name: String!
  }

  input AddBookInput {
    title: String!
    authorId: ID!
  }

  type Query {
    books: [Book!]!
    authors: [Author!]!
    book(id: ID!): Book
    author(id: ID!): Author
  }

  type Mutation {
    addAuthor(input: AddAuthorInput!): Author!
    addBook(input: AddBookInput!): Book!
  }
`;
ğŸ’» Step 3: Resolvers with Relationships
const resolvers = {
  Query: {
    books: async () => {
      const [rows] = await pool.query("SELECT * FROM books");
      return rows;
    },
    authors: async () => {
      const [rows] = await pool.query("SELECT * FROM authors");
      return rows;
    },
    book: async (_, { id }) => {
      const [rows] = await pool.query("SELECT * FROM books WHERE id = ?", [id]);
      return rows[0];
    },
    author: async (_, { id }) => {
      const [rows] = await pool.query("SELECT * FROM authors WHERE id = ?", [id]);
      return rows[0];
    }
  },

  Mutation: {
    addAuthor: async (_, { input }) => {
      const [result] = await pool.query("INSERT INTO authors (name) VALUES (?)", [
        input.name
      ]);
      return { id: result.insertId, name: input.name };
    },
    addBook: async (_, { input }) => {
      const { title, authorId } = input;
      const [result] = await pool.query(
        "INSERT INTO books (title, authorId) VALUES (?, ?)",
        [title, authorId]
      );
      return { id: result.insertId, title, authorId };
    }
  },

  // Relationships
  Book: {
    author: async (book) => {
      const [rows] = await pool.query("SELECT * FROM authors WHERE id = ?", [
        book.authorId
      ]);
      return rows[0];
    }
  },

  Author: {
    books: async (author) => {
      const [rows] = await pool.query("SELECT * FROM books WHERE authorId = ?", [
        author.id
      ]);
      return rows;
    }
  }
};
